05759nam a22008895i 9780812202557DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20132004pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122025577 a10.9783/97808122025572doi  a(DE-B1597)449113  a(OCoLC)979591618  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aHIS0220002bisacsh04a820.989241 aLampert, Lisa, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGender and Jewish Difference from Paul to Shakespeare /cLisa Lampert. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2013] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Middle Ages Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t1. Introduction: Made, Not Born -- t2. The Hermeneutics of Difference -- t3. Reprioritizing the Prioress's Tale -- t4. Creating the Christian in Late Medieval East Anglian Drama -- t5. "O what a goodly outside falsehood hath!" Exegesis and Identity in The Merchant of Venice -- tConclusion -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlthough representations of medieval Christians and Christianity are rarely subject to the same scholarly scrutiny as those of Jews and Judaism, "the Christian" is as constructed a term, category, and identity as "the Jew." Medieval Christian authors created complex notions of Christian identity through strategic use of representations of Others: idealized Jewish patriarchs or demonized contemporary Jews; Woman represented as either virgin or whore. In Western thought, the Christian was figured as spiritual and masculine, defined in opposition to the carnal, feminine, and Jewish.Women and Jews are not simply the Other for the Christian exegetical tradition, however; they also represent sources of origin, as one cannot conceive of men without women or of Christianity without Judaism. The bifurcated representations of Woman and Jew found in the literature of the Middle Ages and beyond reflect the uneasy figurations of women and Jews as both insiders and outsiders to Christian society.Gender and Jewish Difference from Paul to Shakespeare provides the first extended examination of the linkages of gender and Jewish difference in late medieval and early modern English literature. Focusing on representations of Jews and women in Chaucer's Canterbury Tales, selections from medieval drama, and Shakespeare's Merchant of Venice, Lampert explores the ways in which medieval and early modern authors used strategies of opposition to—and identification with—figures of Jews and women to create individual and collective Christian identities. This book shows not only how these questions are interrelated in the texts of medieval and early modern England but how they reveal the distinct yet similarly paradoxical places held by Woman and Jew within a longer tradition of Western thought that extends to the present day.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aChristian drama, EnglishzEnglandvEast AngliaxHistory and criticism. 0aChristian drama, EnglishzEnglandzEast AngliaxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish dramavTo 1500xHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish dramayTo 1500xHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literaturevMiddle English, 1100-1500xHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literaturevMiddle English. 0aEnglish literatureyMiddle English, 1100-1500xHistory and criticism. 0aJews in literature. 4aLiterature. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aGender Studies.  aJewish Studies.  aLiterature.  aMedieval and Renaissance Studies.  aReligion.  aReligious Studies.  aWomen's Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Co